<worksheet label="ws-act-8a-2-3">
  <activity xml:id="act-8a-2-3">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        This activity builds on <xref ref="act-8a-2-2">Activity</xref>, and only changes one key thing: the location where the approximation is centered.  Again, we let <m>f(x) = \ln(x)</m>, and recall that <m>f</m> is only defined for <m>x \gt 0</m>.  Here, we choose to work with an approximation centered at <m>a=2</m>, and find the degree <m>4</m> Taylor polynomial approximation 
        <me>
          T_4(x) = c_0 + c_1 (x-2) + c_2 (x-2)^2 + c_3(x-2)^3 + c_4(x-2)^4
        </me>.
        
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="0.25cm" xml:id="act-8a-2-3-task-0">
      <statement>
        <p>
          We recall <m>f'(x)</m>, <m>f''(x)</m>, <m>f'''(x)</m>, and <m>f^{(4)}(x)</m> from our work in <xref ref="act-8a-2-2">Activity</xref>, and then compute <m>f'(2)</m>, <m>f''(2)</m>, <m>f'''(2)</m>, and <m>f^{(4)}(2)</m>.  Enter the updated results in the blanks below.
          
          
          <md><mrow>k \amp= 0 \amp f(x) \amp= \ln(x) \amp f(2) \amp= <fillin characters="5"/></mrow><mrow>k \amp= 1 \amp f'(x) \amp= x^{-1} \amp f'(2) \amp= <fillin characters="5"/></mrow><mrow>k \amp= 2 \amp f''(x) \amp= (-1)x^{-2} \amp f''(2) \amp= <fillin characters="5"/></mrow><mrow>k \amp= 3 \amp f'''(x) \amp= (-2)(-1)x^{-3}  \amp f'''(2) \amp= <fillin characters="5"/></mrow><mrow>k \amp= 4 \amp f^{(4)}(x) \amp= (-3)(-2)(-1)x^{-4}  \amp f^{(4)}(2) \amp= <fillin characters="5"/></mrow></md></p>
        </statement>
        <hint/>
        <answer>
          <tabular top="none" bottom="none">
            <row>
              <cell halign="right">
                <m>f(x) =</m>
              </cell>
              <cell>
                <m>\ln(x)</m>
              </cell>
              <cell halign="right">
                <m>f(2) =</m>
              </cell>
              <cell>
                <m>\ln(2)</m>
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell halign="right">
                <m>f'(x) = </m>
              </cell>
              <cell>
                <m>x^{-1}</m>
              </cell>
              <cell halign="right">
                <m>f'(2) = </m>
              </cell>
              <cell>
                <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell halign="right">
                <m>f''(x) = </m>
              </cell>
              <cell>
                <m>-1 \cdot x^{-2}</m>
              </cell>
              <cell halign="right">
                <m>f''(2) = </m>
              </cell>
              <cell>
                <m>-\frac{1}{2^2}</m>
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell halign="right">
                <m>f'''(x) = </m>
              </cell>
              <cell>
                <m>(-2)(-1)x^{-3}</m>
              </cell>
              <cell halign="right">
                <m>f'''(2) = </m>
              </cell>
              <cell>
                <m>\frac{(-2)(-1)}{2^3}</m>
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell halign="right">
                <m>f^{(4)}(x) = </m>
              </cell>
              <cell>
                <m>(-3)(-2)(-1)x^{-4}</m>
              </cell>
              <cell halign="right">
                <m>f^{(4)}(2) = </m>
              </cell>
              <cell>
                <m>\frac{(-3)(-2)(-1)}{2^4}</m>
              </cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Let <m>f(x) = \ln(x)</m> and consider the degree <m>4</m> Taylor polynomial approximation 
            <me>
              T_4(x) = c_0 + c_1 (x-2) + c_2 (x-2)^2 + c_3(x-2)^3 + c_4(x-2)^4
            </me>.
          </p>
          <tabular top="none" bottom="none"><row><cell halign="right"><m>f(x) =</m></cell><cell><m>\ln(x)</m></cell><cell halign="right"><m>f(2) =</m></cell><cell><m>\ln(2)</m></cell></row><row><cell halign="right"><m>f'(x) = </m></cell><cell><m>x^{-1}</m></cell><cell halign="right"><m>f'(2) = </m></cell><cell><m>\frac{1}{2}</m></cell></row><row><cell halign="right"><m>f''(x) = </m></cell><cell><m>-1 \cdot x^{-2}</m></cell><cell halign="right"><m>f''(2) = </m></cell><cell><m>-\frac{1}{2^2}</m></cell></row><row><cell halign="right"><m>f'''(x) = </m></cell><cell><m>(-2)(-1)x^{-3}</m></cell><cell halign="right"><m>f'''(2) = </m></cell><cell><m>\frac{(-2)(-1)}{2^3}</m></cell></row><row><cell halign="right"><m>f^{(4)}(x) = </m></cell><cell><m>(-3)(-2)(-1)x^{-4}</m></cell><cell halign="right"><m>f^{(4)}(2) = </m></cell><cell><m>\frac{(-3)(-2)(-1)}{2^4}</m></cell></row></tabular>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="2cm" xml:id="act-8a-2-3-task-1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use your work in (<xref ref="act-8a-2-3-task-0" text="local"/>) along with the fact that the coefficients of the Taylor polynomial are determined by <m>c_k = \frac{f^{(k)}(a)}{k!}</m> to determine <m>T_4(x) = c_0 + c_1 (x-2) + c_2 (x-2)^2 + c_3(x-2)^3 + c_4(x-2)^4</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint/>
        <answer>
          <p><m>T_4(x) = \ln(2) + \frac{1}{2}(x-2) - \frac{1}{2 \cdot 2^2} (x-2)^2 + \frac{1}{3 \cdot 2^3}(x-2)^3 - \frac{1}{4 \cdot 2^4}(x-2)^4</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We see that
            <md><mrow>T_4(x) =\mathstrut \amp c_0 + c_1 (x-2) + c_2 (x-2)^2 + c_3(x-2)^3 + c_4(x-2)^4</mrow><mrow>=\mathstrut \amp \ln(2) + \frac{1}{2}(x-2) - \frac{1}{2! 2^2} (x-2)^2 + \frac{(-2)(-1)}{3! 2^3}(x-2)^3 + \frac{(-3)(-2)(-1)}{4! 2^4}(x-2)^4</mrow><mrow>=\mathstrut \amp \ln(2) + \frac{1}{2}(x-2) - \frac{1}{2 \cdot 2^2} (x-2)^2 + \frac{1}{3 \cdot 2^3}(x-2)^3 - \frac{1}{4 \cdot 2^4}(x-2)^4</mrow></md>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="0.25cm" xml:id="act-8a-2-3-task-2">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use appropriate technology to plot <m>f(x) = \ln(x)</m>, its tangent line, <m>T_1(x) = \ln(2) + \frac{1}{2}(x - 2)</m>, and <m>T_4(x)</m> on the same axes in the window shown <xref ref="F-8a-2-act-3">Figure</xref>. 
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="F-8a-2-act-3">
            <caption>The function <m>f(x)=\ln(x)</m> and its degree <m>1</m> Taylor approximation  <m>T_1(x) = \ln(2) + \frac{1}{2}(x - 2)</m> near the point <m>(2,f(2))</m>.
            </caption>
            <image width="50%" source="images/8a_2_act_3"/>
          </figure>
          <p>
            What do you notice?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint/>
        <answer>
          <image width="50%" source="images/8a_2_act_3_soln"/>
          <p><m>T_4(x)</m> provides a much better approximation of <m>f(x)</m> near <m>a = 2</m> and on a wider interval.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Plotting <m>f(x) = \ln(x)</m>, <m>T_1(x) = \ln(2) + \frac{1}{2}(x - 2)</m>, and <m>T_4(x)</m>,
          </p>
          <image width="50%" source="images/8a_2_act_3_soln"/>
          <p>
            we observe, as expected, that <m>T_4(x)</m> provides a much better approximation of <m>f(x)</m> near <m>a = 2</m> and on a wider interval.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="act-8a-2-3-task-3">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>|f(x) - T_4(x)|</m> for several different <m>x</m> values (you might find it helpful to use a slider in <em>Desmos</em>); for approximately what values of <m>x</m> is it true that <m>|f(x) - T_4(x)| \lt 0.1</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint/>
        <answer>
          <p><m>|f(x) - T_4(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for approximately <m>0.58 \lt x \lt 3.95</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Using a slider in Desmos, we see that<m>|f(x) - T_4(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for approximately <m>0.58 \lt x \lt 3.95</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="act-8a-2-3-task-4">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the patterns you observe in parts (<xref ref="act-8a-2-3-task-0" text="local"/>) and (<xref ref="act-8a-2-3-task-1" text="local"/>) to conjecture formulas for <m>T_5(x)</m> and <m>T_6(x)</m>.  
          </p>
          <p>	
            For about what interval of <m>x</m>-values is it true that <m>|f(x) - T_5(x)| \lt 0.1</m>?  What about <m>|f(x) - T_6(x)| \lt 0.1</m>?  How is this different from what we observed with the Taylor approximations centered at <m>a = 1</m> in <xref ref="act-8a-2-2">Activity</xref>?  How is it similar? 
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint/>
        <answer>
          <p><m>
            T_5(x) = \ln(2) + \frac{1}{2}(x-2) - \frac{1}{2 \cdot 2^2} (x-2)^2 + \frac{1}{3 \cdot 2^3}(x-2)^3 - \frac{1}{4 \cdot 2^4}(x-2)^4 + \frac{1}{5 \cdot 2^5} (x-2)^5
          </m>; 
          
          <m>
            T_6(x) = \ln(2) + \frac{1}{2}(x-2) - \frac{1}{2 \cdot 2^2} (x-2)^2 + \frac{1}{3 \cdot 2^3}(x-2)^3 - \frac{1}{4 \cdot 2^4}(x-2)^4 + \frac{1}{5 \cdot 2^5} (x-2)^5 - \frac{1}{6 \cdot 2^6} (x-2)^6
          </m>.  
        </p>
        <p><m>|f(x) - T_5(x)| \lt 0.1</m>  for roughly <m>0.48 \lt x \lt 4</m>; <m>|f(x) - T_6(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for about <m>0.42 \lt x lt 4</m>.  By moving to <m>a = 2</m>, which is further away from the asymptote at <m>x = 0</m>, we can get approximations of <m>ln(x)</m> that seem to be good all the way up to <m>x = 4</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Based on the pattern in (<xref ref="act-8a-2-3-task-0" text="local"/>) and <m>T_4(x) = \ln(2) + \frac{1}{2}(x-2) - \frac{1}{2 \cdot 2^2} (x-2)^2 + \frac{1}{3 \cdot 2^3}(x-2)^3 - \frac{1}{4 \cdot 2^4}(x-2)^4</m>, we expect that
          <me>
            T_5(x) = \ln(2) + \frac{1}{2}(x-2) - \frac{1}{2 \cdot 2^2} (x-2)^2 + \frac{1}{3 \cdot 2^3}(x-2)^3 - \frac{1}{4 \cdot 2^4}(x-2)^4 + \frac{1}{5 \cdot 2^5} (x-2)^5
          </me> 
          and 
          <me>
            T_6(x) = \ln(2) + \frac{1}{2}(x-2) - \frac{1}{2 \cdot 2^2} (x-2)^2 + \frac{1}{3 \cdot 2^3}(x-2)^3 - \frac{1}{4 \cdot 2^4}(x-2)^4 + \frac{1}{5 \cdot 2^5} (x-2)^5 - \frac{1}{6 \cdot 2^6} (x-2)^6
          </me>.  
        </p>
        <p>	
          When we increase the degree to <m>n = 5</m>, we see that <m>|f(x) - T_5(x)| \lt 0.1</m>  for roughly <m>0.48 \lt x \lt 4</m>, and if we go to <m>n = 6</m>, <m>|f(x) - T_6(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for about <m>0.42 \lt x lt 4</m>.  This is similar to the Taylor approximations centered at <m>a = 1</m> in <xref ref="act-8a-2-2">Activity</xref> in that there's an upper bound on the approximation interval and that the width of the interval doesn't increase much with the higher degree, but it's different in that the interval of accuracy is wider.  It seems that by moving to <m>a = 2</m>, which is further away from the asymptote at <m>x = 0</m>, we can get approximations of <m>ln(x)</m> that are good all the way up to <m>x = 4</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <hint/>
  </activity>
</worksheet>